  "prompt": "How do jellyfish breath?",
  "response": "Jellyfish do not breathe in the same way that vertebrates like humans do because they lack specialized respiratory systems, such as lungs or gills. Instead, jellyfish rely on diffusion to exchange gases. \n\nThe body of a jellyfish is composed of a gelatinous substance called mesoglea, and its simple anatomy allows for the diffusion of oxygen and carbon dioxide directly through their skin. Water flows through their bodies, and oxygen from the water diffuses into their cells while carbon dioxide produced by cellular processes diffuses out into the water. \n\nThis passive exchange is sufficient for their needs, as jellyfish have relatively low metabolic rates and live in environments where oxygen is available in the surrounding water.",
